04733nam a22006255i 9780520938359DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209383597 a10.1525/97805209383592doi  a(DE-B1597)518763  a(OCoLC)973979764  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE184.E2G46 2005aE184.E2 G46 2005eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.48/8914110731 aGeorge, Sheba, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen Women Come First :bGender and Class in Transnational Migration /cSheba George. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations And Tables -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Contradictions Of Gender When Women Immigrate First -- t2. Work: Nursing, Women'S Networks, And Men "Tied To A Stake" -- t3. Home: Redoing Gender In Immigrant Households -- t4. Community: Creating Little Kerala And The Paradox Of "Men Who Play" In The Church -- t5. Transnational Connections: The Janus-Faced Production Of An Immigrant Community -- t6. Conclusions -- tAppendix 1: Interview Participants By Household Type -- tAppendix 2: Types Of Nursing Jobs -- tAppendix 3: Transnational Organizational Structure Of The Indian Orthodox Church -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith a subtle yet penetrating understanding of the intricate interplay of gender, race, and class, Sheba George examines an unusual immigration pattern to analyze what happens when women who migrate before men become the breadwinners in the family. Focusing on a group of female nurses who moved from India to the United States before their husbands, she shows that this story of economic mobility and professional achievement conceals underlying conditions of upheaval not only in the families and immigrant community but also in the sending community in India. This richly textured and impeccably researched study deftly illustrates the complex reconfigurations of gender and class relations concealed behind a quintessential American success story. When Women Come First explains how men who lost social status in the immigration process attempted to reclaim ground by creating new roles for themselves in their church. Ironically, they were stigmatized by other upper class immigrants as men who needed to "play in the church" because the "nurses were the bosses" in their homes. At the same time, the nurses were stigmatized as lower class, sexually loose women with too much independence. George's absorbing story of how these women and men negotiate this complicated network provides a groundbreaking perspective on the shifting interactions of two nations and two cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEast IndianszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aMan-woman relationshipszIndia. 0aMan-woman relationshipszUnited States. 0aNurseszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 0aTransnationalism. 0aWomen foreign workersxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomen immigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWomen, East IndianxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aWomen, East IndianzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938359423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520938359.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-20